SIFT takes a query sequence and uses multiple alignment information to predict tolerated and deleterious substitutions for every position of the query sequence.  Positions with normalized probabilities less than 0.05 are predicted to be deleterious; those greater than or equal to 0.05 are predicted to be tolerated.

Description: Functional prediction score for non-syn variants from all LJB databases (ljb_sift; ljb_mt; ljb_phylop;ljb_lrt;ljb_gerp++)

Functional prediction score for non-syn variants from LRT provided by dbNSFP (higher score represents functionally more deleterious. It ranges from 0 to 1. This score needs to be combined with other information prediction. If a threshold has to be picked up under some situation; 0.995 can be used as starting point.

Functional prediction score for non-syn variants from Mutation Taster provided by dbNSFP  (higher score represents functionally more deleterious). The score ranges from 0 to 1. Similar to LRT; the prediction is not entirely depending on the score alone. But if a threshold has to be picked; 0.5 is the recommended as the starting point.

Conservation score provided by dbNSFP which is re-scaled from original phylop score. The new score ranges from 0-1 with larger scores signifying higher conservation. A recommended cutoff threshold is 0.95. If the score > 0.95; the prediction is 'conservative'. if the score <0.95; the prediction is 'non-conservative'.

Functional prediction score for non-syn variants from Polyphen2 provided by dbNSFP (higher score represents functionally more deleterious). Scores greater than .85 are 'probably damaging'; scores from 0.15-0.85 are 'possibly damaging'; and scores below 0.15 are 'benign'.

Functional prediction score for non-syn variants from Polyphen2 provided by dbNSFP (higher score represents functionally more deleterious). Scores greater than .85 are 'probably damaging'; scores from 0.15-0.85 are 'possibly damaging'; and scores below 0.15 are 'benign'.
